  "prompt": "How does magnesium oxide react with water?",
  "response": "Magnesium oxide (MgO) reacts with water (H\u2082O) in a slow process to form magnesium hydroxide [Mg(OH)\u2082]. This reaction is classified as a hydration reaction. The chemical equation for this reaction is:\n\n\\[ \\text{MgO} + \\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\rightarrow \\text{Mg(OH)}_2 \\]\n\nHere\u2019s a breakdown of the process:\n\n1. **Reaction Mechanism**: Magnesium oxide is a basic oxide, and when it comes into contact with water, it gradually reacts to produce magnesium hydroxide, which is a weak base.\n2. **Exothermic Reaction**: The reaction is exothermic, meaning it releases heat as it proceeds.\n3. **Solubility**: Magnesium hydroxide is sparingly soluble in water, so the reaction is relatively slow and depends on the surface area of the MgO and the temperature of the water.\n\nThis reaction is commonly used in industrial processes, such as in the production of magnesium hydroxide for use in antacids and other applications.",
